        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/resident.ngo/{size}/54379_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-10-25T17:05:11.826Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Feature request: <strong>implement a truly phishing-resistant second-factor authentication method for all Signal accounts</strong>. Alternatively, introduce an opt-in ‚ÄúAdvanced Protection‚Äù mode that enforces phishing-resistant authentication for users who enable it. Current protections (registration lock, warnings and PIN) are insufficient against targeted social-engineering attacks by APT hacker groups that trick high-risk users into handing over SMS codes, PINs, or scanning QR codes.</p>\n<p>Phishing-resistant 2FA (FIDO2/U2F/passkeys) as well as hardened device-addition workflow would significantly increase the effort and cost required for threat actors to execute account takeover.</p>\n<h1><a name=\"p-278089-why-it-is-important-1\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-278089-why-it-is-important-1\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Why it is important</h1>\n<p>Russian and Belarusian APT groups have been conducting targeted phishing operations to compromise Signal  accounts. Through sophisticated social engineering tactics, these threat actors trick victims into revealing SMS codes, PINs, or scanning malicious QR codes, enabling unauthorized access to compromised accounts or accounts takeover:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/blog/topics/threat-intelligence/russia-targeting-signal-messenger\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://cloud.google.com/blog/topics/threat-intelligence/russia-targeting-signal-messenger</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://resident.ngo/lab/writeups/signal-phishing-belarus-2025/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://resident.ngo/lab/writeups/signal-phishing-belarus-2025/</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://cyberhub.am/en/blog/2025/09/23/technical-writeup-signal-account-takeover-ato-phishing-campaign/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://cyberhub.am/en/blog/2025/09/23/technical-writeup-signal-account-takeover-ato-phishing-campaign/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>For high-risk individuals such as journalists, activists, and politicians, account compromise can have severe consequences including imprisonment or torture. While education and awareness efforts, supported by recent real-world examples, do help, they cannot completely eliminate the risk for the vast majority of users. To address this, we recommend implementing technical mitigations that make remote phishing-based account breaches significantly more difficult.</p>\n<p>Phishing-resistant 2FA became the de-facto standard years ago for high-profile users of Microsoft, Google and Apple services:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/entra/identity/authentication/phishing-resistant-authentication-videos\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/entra/identity/authentication/phishing-resistant-authentication-videos</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://landing.google.com/intl/en_in/advancedprotection/\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://landing.google.com/intl/en_in/advancedprotection/</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://support.apple.com/en-gb/102637\" rel=\"noopener nofollow ugc\">https://support.apple.com/en-gb/102637</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h1><a name=\"p-278089-threat-model-2\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-278089-threat-model-2\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Threat model</h1>\n<p><strong>Adversary:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Can exploit social-engineering techniques to manipulate victims into performing certain actions, such as pressing buttons, forwarding one-time verification codes, revealing PINs, or scanning malicious QR codes.</li>\n<li><strong>Cannot</strong> install malware or remote access trojans on victim‚Äôs device (assume victim‚Äôs devices are not compromised).</li>\n<li>Does <strong>not</strong> have physical access to any device used to access the target‚Äôs Signal account.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><a name=\"p-278089-goal-3\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-278089-goal-3\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a><strong>Goal:</strong></h3>\n<p>Ensure that attackers cannot compromise a Signal account even if a victim is successfully tricked into disclosing codes/PINs or scanning malicious QR codes provided by attackers.</p>\n<h1><a name=\"p-278089-proposed-solutions-prioritized-4\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-278089-proposed-solutions-prioritized-4\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Proposed Solutions (prioritized)</h1>\n<h2><a name=\"p-278089-option-a-recommended-ideal-fido2u2f-hardware-keys-or-passkeys-as-the-primary-phishing-resistant-authentication-factor-5\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-278089-option-a-recommended-ideal-fido2u2f-hardware-keys-or-passkeys-as-the-primary-phishing-resistant-authentication-factor-5\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Option A ‚Äî Recommended / Ideal: FIDO2/U2F hardware keys or Passkeys as the primary phishing-resistant authentication factor</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Add support for both FIDO2/U2F hardware keys and passkeys in account enrollment and device-linking flows.</li>\n<li>Require that a <strong>new device</strong> can be added (linked) to an account only after it <span class=\"bbcode-u\">(</span>the new device, rather than the already linked one) presents a registered phishing‚Äëresistant credential: either a FIDO2/U2F hardware key or an account‚Äëbound passkey.</li>\n<li>When FIDO2/U2F hardware keys or passkeys are added, all weaker flows for device migration should be disabled. SMS-only, PIN-only, or QR-only verification methods for device linking should be disallowed unless the new device can present the registered FIDO2/U2F hardware key or a passkey.</li>\n<li>Implement support for multiple registered security keys per account (to ensure recoverability), with a recommended minimum of 2 keys.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2><a name=\"p-278089-option-b-partial-layered-mitigations-if-fido2passkeys-is-not-supported-6\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-278089-option-b-partial-layered-mitigations-if-fido2passkeys-is-not-supported-6\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Option B ‚Äî Partial / layered mitigations if FIDO2/passkeys is not supported</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Enforce device proximity checks when adding a new device: require both devices to be on the same LAN or paired via Bluetooth before a QR scan or device-transfer flow can proceed.</li>\n<li>If Registration Lock is enabled and there is an active session in the last _N_ days (e.g., 7 days), <strong>do not</strong> allow immediate account migration to a new smartphone via SMS/PIN/QR. Instead:\n<ul>\n<li>Implement mandatory cooldown period (e.g., 24 hours) after initiating account migration.</li>\n<li>Display persistent visual warnings across all previously connected (linked) devices with countdown timer, similar to Gmail‚Äôs email‚Äëforwarding alert.</li>\n<li>Provide clear ‚ÄúCancel Transfer‚Äù option accessible from all connected devices.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Disallow any phone‚Äënumber change for 24 hours after the Signal account was migrated to a new smartphone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h1><a name=\"p-278089-validatingmaking-sure-feature-requirements-are-met-7\" class=\"anchor\" href=\"#p-278089-validatingmaking-sure-feature-requirements-are-met-7\" aria-label=\"Heading link\"></a>Validating/making sure feature requirements are met</h1>\n<p>Even if victims are successfully tricked into disclosing SMS codes, PINs, or scanning malicious QR codes, attackers MUST not be able complete the registration process (link a new device or move Signal to the new device) <strong>unless</strong> they also provide a registered FIDO2/U2F key or a passkey.</p>",
